
[1]spurt

   SPURT, v.t. [The English word has suffered a transposition of letters.
   It is from the root of sprout, which see.] To throw out, as liquid in a
   stream; to drive or force out with violence, as a liquid from a pipe or
   small orifice; as, to spurt water from the mouth, or other liquid from
   a tube.

   SPURT, v.i. To gush or issue out in a stream, as liquor from a cask; to
   rush from a confined place in a small stream.

   Then the small jet, which hasty hands unlock, spurts in the gardners
   eyes who turns the cock.

                                  SPURT, n.

   1. A sudden or violent ejection or gushing of a liquid substance from a
   tube, orifice or other confined place; a jet.

   2. A sudden or short occasion or exigency; sudden effort. [Vulgar.]
